That’s when she met Yearwood, who was in Malawi working for World Vision. “My project,” said Yearwood, who grew up in Guilderland, N.Y., “was basically to coordinate the drill rigs, making sure the drilling went quickly. I had two helicopter pads up in the mountains where the machete-wielding drillers would have a beer and wait for the drill to arrive. It was pretty intense. I would just remember that I was 19, and I felt like I had no business being there.”“I cannot live in a place where people got lynched for being witches, just like they got lynched for having darker skin,” said Galanz, who works for the recruitment firm BCG. For her, within the first week, in broad daylight, Yearwood had people point at her, accusing her of “being a witch. She saw in Lusaka, Zambia, kids eating dirt.
